[Cases like this can be extremely frustrating and baffling. It may require a case coordinator to keep careful notes on every case, including photographs and records of the time of year, temperatures, rainfalls, etc and a botanist to walk the pastures at various stages of growth. It may be a plant, or a fungus. It may occur early in the plant cycle, or only after the plant has matured and produced seeds. It may take a lot of soil testing, even in years when there are no losses, to start seeing any connection between cases. It is also important to know vaccination histories and pasture histories of any chemicals applied.

This is a challenging case and may or may not involve even a new and as yet undiagnosed disease. Research is needed and it may be up to the government to fund such research.

In 2014 New South Wales experienced what was called 3D syndrome, drooling, diarrhea, and death. But this syndrome sounds quite different. - Mod.TG

Maps of Australia can be seen at http://maps.unomaha.edu/peterson/funda/MapLinks/Australia/Australia_files/image001.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4241003,53352. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
